As a matter of fact, the XTR-12 is a short-stroke piston-driven gas-operated shotgun and comes with a rotating bolt head and six locking lugs; the XTR-12 bolt is indeed an AR-10 type bolt beefed up in size for the 12-gauge shotshells. Feeding through single-column detachable magazines holding two, five or seven 12-gauge shotshells with a 76mm/3" ("Magnum") case, the UTAS XTR-12 semi-automatic shotgun comes with a 18,5" long 4140 stainless steel machined barrel adapted to use several types of chokes; the bolt is manufactured of the same 4140 stainless steel, while the structure is manufactured out of lightweight aluminum alloy and magnesium, in order to keep the weight under acceptable levels. The UTAS International XTR-12 semi-automatic shotgun comes with an M4-type ergonomic pistol grip and a five-positions collapsing polymer stock, and strips in two receivers just like an AR-15; its total lenght ranges between 96,5cm and more or less 1 metre, depending from the stock extension. The XTR-12 is 3,6 kilograms long and sports fully ambidextrous controls and several MIL-STD-1913 "Picatinny" rails for several types of aiming devices or tactical accessories. title: For Sale:  "M1 Carbine" Mosin
postcontent: For sale, an "M1 Carbine" Mosin. M91/30 Tula Arsenal Mosin-Nagant made in 1939. She was bought as a sporter and further modified by me and some friends. Gun has had a front sight from an M1 Carbine fitted onto the barrel along with an M1 Carbine conical flash hider similar to the kind used in Korea welded on. Weld could be prettier but its sound and I've put at least a hundred rounds downrange after this modification. The idea behind the project was to affix a pistol grip, folding stock, and scout scope to it and use the M1 sights as backup, they perfectly line up with the Mosin's rear sight but I'm not going to lie, at some angles it can be hard to see over the cone. Rifle does shoot high but rifling is good.The stock is original and very dinged up, very large gash towards the end of the barrel which was covered up with electrical tape, the idea was to make the rifle look like something out of "Mad Max" and in combination with the battle worn stock and tape, it looks very weathered. I simply don't have the time or money to finish this project so I'm selling it.Hoping she finds a new home with an owner who will continue work on "Mad Maxing" her and accurizing her or take the gun in a different direction.I understand that the modifications may not be to everyone's taste, accordingly asking for $120 OBO
